## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

### Pattern Classification

Your code has **three** patterns that break on .NET 8:

| API | Problem on .NET 8 | Replacement |
|-----|-------------------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — cleanup never runs | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — replaces the ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. Cooperative cancellation doesn't auto-rethrow.
                // The loop condition will exit naturally on next iteration.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal the token — replaces Thread.Abort()

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. With cooperative cancellation,
            // this means GetNextItem or ProcessItem isn't checking the token.
            // Log a warning — you cannot force-kill a managed thread in .NET 8.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### Critical Changes Explained

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept the token.** This is the biggest pitfall. If it blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection`, socket, or `ManualResetEvent`), cancellation won't work unless the blocking call is token-aware:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, Thread.Abort was the only way out
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// AFTER — wakes up when cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If you're using `Thread.Sleep` to poll:
```csharp
// BEFORE
Thread.Sleep(1000);

// AFTER — wakes immediately on cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000);
```

**2. `Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `Thread.Join(TimeSpan)`** — `Join` is strictly better; it actually waits for the thread to finish rather than hoping 2 seconds is enough.

**3. `IDisposable`** — `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed. Always wrap ownership in `IDisposable`.

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| Not passing token to `GetNextItem` | If it blocks on I/O or a wait handle, `Cancel()` has no effect — the thread hangs forever. There is no fallback equivalent to `Abort()`. |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish cancellation from other `OperationCanceledException` sources. |
| Expecting cancellation to be instant | Cooperative cancellation only fires at checkpoints. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running. |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Causes timer and callback leaks. Always dispose it. |
| Assuming `Thread.Abort` has any workaround | It does **not**. On .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` unconditionally. There is no flag, no config, and no shim. The code *must* cooperate. |
